segments.text: But the spinoff from those really adds to the people care.
Sure.
Back to the profile of the veterinarian, skilled, technically skilled, good public relations, like people, passionate and humane toward animals.
Anything else?
Okay, let's talk, if you will, a bit now about the conversion or changes in the field of veterinary medicine, say in the southwest in Texas.

moving essentially from the large animal uh rural production orientation to something else and i don't want the words in your mouth you just sort of give us an image of how things have changed of course it follows it follows the training of people we were an agrarian society i grew up in the agrarian society my daddy was a little patch farmer you know geeked out a living
turning the soil, and we had animals, and we respected the animals.
The animals worked for us, and if we cared for the animals, they'd do the work for us.
They were important to us, and we had them to eat.
We had hogs, and we killed hogs, and we killed calves, and all that, and we ate them.
Right over the farm, we didn't go out and buy the reef or the port.
That was produced right there on the farm.
And, uh,
Animals were very important out there.
And there was a need for the care of those animals.
The veterinarian's lifestyle then was individual animal treatment.
Pure and simple.
The old cow got sick and he was called to treat the old cow.
The dog wasn't as fortunate.
He could go.
didn't even call the veterinarian for a dog or take him to the veterinarian either.
But the dog was an essential utilitarian animal around the place, but you can get more dogs very fast.
And so he wasn't as important.
Oh, he had his pets, yeah, but mostly they were utilitarian.
They didn't come in the house, and we didn't pet them like we do today, but I had a little dog.
that I thought the world of when I was a kid, the little squirrel dogs and things.
I found a lot of squirrels.
Highly utilitarian.
You bet.
And sheepdogs and all those, you know, that handle little goats and herd them.
But the dog was a dog and not a people and they had no rights.
But we treated them nicely.
We fed them carefully.
and gave them a good place to sleep and all that.
Tried to treat them right.
And as a kid, we were taught that.
Well, people began to move to the town.
You know, urbanization took place, and country people moved to town, and country people had been related to animals out there in the country.
And they got into the town,
concrete jungles, and those animals weren't there, and they missed those animals.
They longed for those animals.
So they began slowly to take in pets.
Now these are really pets then, you see.
They're not really utilitarian, but they're pets.
They're satisfying the emotions of people rather than the economics of people.
So it went from economics to emotional.
And pets now are emotional characters.
So the small animal practice then began to come on the picture, all for what people want.
Now, all the time and all the way through, it has been bound by what people want.

Sometimes in committees and groups that are surveying and evaluating the veterinary medical profession, it's easy for those in the profession to say, well, we did this, we concocted this, we dreamed this up for the good of the people.
And that usually isn't the case.
It was what the people were telling you to do is what you did.
You are responding to what people will inform you.
Do you see that through time as well, that your medicine has been reactive rather than...
Yes, it's still reactive.
Yeah.
Rather than proactive.
Even with the public health issues, which is something I think we're going to need to look at.
Well, I think even with public health, yeah, we're reactive.
Does that bother you?
Are you happy with that?
No.
And we have committee after committee trying to look down the future.
But we're not good enough to see it correctly.
And we react to what people then demand.
And we do what people demand.
If you don't do what people demand,
You can go home.
And veterinary medicine has changed because people have changed, not what we have done as a profession.
Now, when you came in, when you got your DVM,
Were many people going into small animal practice, in other words?
There were some.
There were some.
There were some.
But most of them, even then, were to give you a little practice.
It's a large animal practice.
And you know, at that point in time and until this day, there is the perception out there among applicants
that what we want is a large animal practitioner.
And they go to the commissions committee.
Well, what are you going to do?
What kind of practice are you going to do?
I'm going to have a large animal practitioner.
Because they think that's what we want to hear.
That isn't true anymore.
It used to be.
And that old image is still hanging on there.
Right now we're looking for more researchers than practitioners.
Where do they go, your research products?
What kind of employment do they go into?
They go into biomedical research of many different kinds.
Is that where your best market is actually?
Yeah.
And this is where we need the most upgrading.
This is where we get our technology also.
is from the research side.
So it's the research and development aspect.
Yeah.
I expect the public perception right now, too, is still that a veterinarian goes into practice.
They go out and they're either a large animal or a small animal, but they are in practice.
They don't see this side of it at all.
People come here.
We've got six people, six families coming this morning, or today, during the course of the day, to this office.
Prospective students.
High school students are off this morning.
And we're going to have six of them today, and I don't have any of the rest of them.
We will have people coming the rest of the week.
These are prospective students.
And as they come to us, they have the idea that we want large animal practitioners.
And we're looking for more researchers than we are large animal practitioners.
We're looking for more large animal practitioners than we are small animal practitioners.
Okay, so that still holds, okay.
We've got a glut of small animal practitioners located in the cities.
How do you know you have a glut?
Well, when I say a glut, it is that there are evidence, there is evidence out there that there's greater competition.
Would you really get that feedback?
You're getting that feedback.
I would assume so, I just...
That's my base there, and whether it's blood or not.
And the employment for large animal people is still pretty strong in the market.
Yes.
It may even be increasing.
We have a small distribution.
This is like medical doctors.
You can't keep the hospitals open in the rural areas.
That's right.
They're closing those hospitals.
They can't make it.
It's the same way back in the 90s.
That's interesting.
There is, and has been for, I don't know, 30 years, I guess, 25 years anyway.
There's been a mild distribution, and it's getting worse.

So I think that's one thing we really want to work on in this book we're trying to write, and that is to try to correctly portray what the profession really is, you know, the dimensions, the profile of a veterinarian, and how they fit into society.
And I think the public image of that is not what it necessarily is.
I guess if we can correct that image, we've done something worthwhile.
One of the concerns, as I've thought about this, that I've had, and I don't want to take the discussion away from you.
Over the years, there has been, from time to time, depending on the personalities involved, there's friction between county agents, for example.
That used to be tough, rough.

As, if this is a true statement, if veterinary practice for whatever reasons tends to, or has tended to congregate in large urban areas, you know, the poor folks out in Tulia or wherever are left with less and less resources to get, you know, to answer their animal needs.
But the age is still there.
You know why?
He doesn't charge them anything.
That's right.
And that's what I'm wondering.
Is that friction... Redeveloping?
Well, I haven't perceived that it's increasing.
It was bad at one time.
It was really, you know, dogfights at one time.
And then it eased off and it got better and better and I...
perceived that it would last several years, that the problem, the real problem, had really gone away.
Now, I'm sure there are instances out there where it still exists.
Of course, the county agent and his staff are out there paid by somebody else to help the rural people.
And they do a good job.
And it's good that they're out there.
But they do it for free.
Now, where they went wrong, and I have to blame the county agents and their staffs, is they got into the practice of medicine.
If they will stick out there to what they have been trained for, there will be no problem.
But when they go over and begin to make diagnoses, well, like looking across the fence, you know, I think that the cows got sold.
That's a diagnosis to that owner.
You're just thinking that, but that's a diagnosis to that owner.
That's what that owner perceives.
And that owner operates on that basis and does not call the veterinarian.
Now, if they could draw the line well enough to say,
Well, you know, I don't know what's the matter with that old cow, but I think you better call the veterinarian and let it sit.
That'll cement the two together, you see.
And they weren't doing that.
Today, they're getting back and doing it.
Now, if it's widening again, I haven't... Are they back together, do you think, because veterinarians have in fact been successful in their public relations tasks?
That not just our farmers...
One of the things I, and this may be my own perception and Aronia's, that's why I wanted to ask you, because you might know for sure.

In the early days, you know, the turn of the century, the teens and the twenties, veterinarians were still kind of new kids on the block, you know, in terms of the public awareness of what they did and the function.
I don't think that's the case anymore.
I think people have a very
It may be erroneous, but they have a definite image about what a veterinarian is good for and when to use it.
Well, the city and the countryside are a little different there.
I think what you described there was the city perception.
The country knew that there were veterinarians, and they were out there.
But there were no pets, essentially, in the city, and there were very few veterinarians in the city.
The veterinarians were out in the countryside.
That's where his bread and butter was.
And so he was practicing out there, and the country people, I think, had no capacity to see the veterinarian.
I'm talking about large animal practice.
I'm not talking about dogs and cats, but the countryside.
I'm talking about cows and horses and sheep and goats and hogs and domestic animals.
And they've had... Production care.
Yeah.
Veterinarians have been caring for those for a long time, and people have used them for a long time.
But as the time changed, why, people in town began to see what veterinarians could do.
But out there in the countryside, when the county agent now went to the place, and the people called the county agent, he was probably more known than the veterinarian out there.
He had more
Publicity.
The veterinary medical profession has been against advertising.
There are some who do.
I see a local here recently on TV advertising.
And the others that are practicing around this city look down upon him for that.
Right or wrong, and I'm not arguing the right or wrong with that at all, but there is a difference there.
They don't want to.
They want to gain their client by their productivity.
And I think that is the honest way to go.
And I hope they'll stay with that.
Produce and people will come to you.
Do it right and people will come to you.
You don't have to tell them about yourself.
Do it right, and they'll come to you.
Now, the county agent, though, and the extension service is throwing out all the time, call your county agent, call your county agent, you see.
And the people out there knew, hey, the county agent can do this.
They're telling me he can.
And the county agent was called out, and then he made the diagnosis.
And the veterinarian that's sitting right there in the same little area resented that.
That's right.
And they were cutting into his practice, you see.
Now, the Agricultural Extension Service worked hard on that business, however, and improved it greatly.
And for the last, oh, 15 years, I would say, I don't think there's been a big problem out there between county agencies.
They understand their positions a little better than they did back then.
In that same vein, Dr. Price, how has the Texas Veterinary Medical Association helped, hindered, or whatever, the profession in Texas and the South?
Could you sort of talk about the relationships between, say, academia, TVMA, TVNA, and the public?
Just how you feel about it as a person.
Did you join TVMA, for example, right away when you got here?
Is that pretty standard procedure that most people join?
Why?
Most by far, not all.
Why did they join you?
What are their expectations?
Well, you need some kind of a professional organization, organizational structure.
You need, we call it professional and call it professional
Because we're supposed to self-impose what we do.
We're supposed to clean up our own acts.
We don't have a political clout somewhere that's saying, you do this.
We're going to do it ourselves.
That's the reason we call ourselves professional.
We clean up our own house.
We do our own thing.
So in a sense, it is a regulatory agency.
It is an intra-professional regulatory agency.
In other words, not from outside, but inside.
Regulating yourselves.
And we need that.
And all the way from the county to the district to the state to the American Veterinary Medical Association is the organization of the chain.
And I don't know how we'd survive without that, because if we didn't have that, everybody's going off on his own, just doing whatever he wants to do, you know.
And I can perceive that, boy, there'd be clashes, and this guy's doing this, and this guy's doing that, and there'd be no...
Which was the major thrust of the early association, apparently.
We went through all the records over there in Austin, and boy, they were on the...
trail of the quacks and I think what the words they used, but quacks was the big one.
Quacks, you bet.
And even when 1911, when the Practice Act was passed, and anybody that had been practicing five years before that was the grandfather clause, you know.
And they were put in the director, though, as NG, non-graduate.
to distinguish them between the graduate and the non-graduate.
And those that were in there that five years could keep on practicing.
Well, I don't know whether any of those are living or not yet.
If not, they're nearly all gone.
What had been the major thrust or efforts of the TDMA, do you think?
Well, I think it's just that.
I think it's just that.
Let's do what we, as a profession, we ought to perform as a profession.
Each of us have an obligation to not just ourselves, to not just our little area, to not just our clients.
We've got an obligation to our profession.
Has there been any direct influence by TVMA, say, on policies of the College of Veterinary Medicine?
either deliberate or subconscious or whatever.
They won.
We decided here at the College of Veterinary Medicine to go on a trimester system.
We were on the semester system for four years.
And this was during the time of
sparsity and it was perceived that we needed to produce more veterinarians.
And this was a, not just Texas, this was a national issue.
And to get to
that will enhance that.
And we studied it in the College of Veterinary Medicine carefully over a period of a couple of years and decided that, you know, we could go three trimesters instead of two semesters.
By doing some things, we can do as much in a trimester as we can do in a semester.
A semester was a little bit longer than a trimester.
But we did such things as all examinations were at 7 o'clock in the morning.
That gave the whole rest of it full day activity.
You can do things like that which put a little more burden on the student.
But they could move and graduate in three years.
We could better utilize our facilities then.
We go all the way through the summer.
The semester system, you go nine months and you're off three months and come back and this clinic over here and these buildings sit here for three months.
You know, what are you doing with them?
We utilize that better.
And the cost of the students is only three years instead of four years.
Maybe the tuition is about the same
is the four-year, but the living cost of this.
You could graduate and be a veterinarian with less money.
There were a whole bunch of good reasons why we did that.
Now, back to your question.
We had to have the sanction of the veterinary medical profession to get that job done.
We needed their help to get that job done.
Oh, the university could have declared that, you know, but that's not the way to go.
We want to go and have everybody satisfied.
And I'll give you some documents right here.
We went to the Texas Veterinary Medical Association and laid out what we wanted to do.
We had no problem.
Let's go.
Now, today, it's a different story today.
The economy today is different.
We've put more veterinarians out there since that time.
And now, out there in the hinterland, they're a little uncomfortable out there about the number of veterinarians out there today.
That was my next question.
I don't think we've got a lot of veterinarians, and I don't think we're going to have a lot of veterinarians.
There are people out there who believe that we do have, and most of those are the people who are in the city and where we have a... Where they may be in.
Yeah, that maldistribution may be playing a part, and a guy comes in two blocks down and sits down and builds a clinic there, it acts on yours, has influence on your own.
So there is competition out there.
And that is hurting us right now.
It's hurting us from several points.
Number one is that high school students out there where that veterinarian is practicing and says, we've got a glut of veterinarians.
I can hardly make a living out of it.
We've been down in economics in Texas.
And as veterinarians, we feel it's economical.
thing in Texas.
We're going to get over it.
But they've been feeling it pretty hard.
And you know, if you've got a dog, a family pet, and you don't have much money, and you have to set your priorities, you're likely not going to take that pet to the veterinarian.
And so they've suffered through this economic period, down economic period.
But as I say, we're going to get over that.
But the high school kids out there get this impression, well, if I can't study veterinary medicine, I mean, if I can't make a living, I don't want to study veterinary medicine.
And we have dissuaded many high school students in our community.
Our number of applicants, applicant pools, is down.
Is that right?
Is that right?
Is down.
Even without any real action.
That's interesting.
And we're concerned about it.
Well, yeah, because there is, the word on the street is, vets can't get jobs.
Yeah.
Yeah.
I mean, I've heard that.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Another thing that we hear, and this is the American Veterinary Medical Association, and it made a mistake.
As it turned out, the American Veterinary Medical Association way back there, oh, I don't know, 1970s, hired R.D.
Little, Incorporated, to survey the country and predict what our veterinary medical manpower should be in the future.
And they did.
And they said, by 1980, you're going to have a blood of veterinarians.
Well, when 1980 came and went, we didn't have a lot of veterinarians.
We have some mild distribution, but we don't have a lot of veterinarians.
But that gets around.
See, back to the high school kids again.
Mamas and Papas will hear that, that you've got a lot of veterinarians, you can't make a living at it.
And shoot, they go somewhere else.
And we have hurt ourselves, and the AVMA has hurt the profession with that study.
That's a good illustration.

Conversely now, has the College of Veterinary Medicine benefited from TVMA in using TVMA perhaps as a spokesman for appropriate legislative appropriations for support for funding or anything like that?
Well, let me be honest and candid with you, and I hope you won't put this in there.
The TVMA...
believes, I really think it believes, it has a great influence in the legislature.
There's no way that the TVM agent have a great influence in the Texas legislature.
There's not enough of us.
OK, certainly Charlie Huff felt that, during his day at least.
I don't know whether that was true or not, but I perceive that.
Well, I don't know how Charlie felt about that.
I felt that he did.
He may have.
They have worked, the TVMA staff have worked, and then we've had other veterinarians that we've pulled into it, too.
And I'm sure they've done good.
They've done some good.
But they're not going to really bolster sufficiently the legislative appropriations for the College of Veterinary Medicine.
They'll go talk to them about it.
They'll go talk to them about it.
And that's better than nothing.
But what I'm saying is,
They don't have the clout to really pull that off.
So you come through Texas A&M, higher education in Texas.
That's your force.
Oh, we'll ask them to do that.
And one of the main reasons we ask them to do that, and here, going off the record, is to let them know that we perceive that they're helping.
Well, they're helping.
But what I'm saying is,
They're believing they're helping more than they really are.
But our relationship, we've got to have a good relationship.
I don't want to go over there and say or say the two and let them think that.
We think here at the College of Veterinary Medicine, they're just dodo's if they go over there and try to do a thing.
They ought to stay out of it.
That isn't what I'm saying at all.
We need them in there.
Yeah, I don't want to make a case for that at all, but that helps me understand the relationship between the association and the college.
There's another thing about relationships, too, that is aggravating between the TDMA and the College of Education, and I don't want to build this thing up.
No, yeah, that's not what it's about.
We're doing well with it.
We graduate a student, and he goes out and goes to work for a veterinarian out there that's been in practice 10 years.
And he looks to that veterinarian that's been in practice 10 years like he is green.
He's unsure, the student, the new graduate.
He's unsure about things.
Well, he should be.
And then the older practitioner out there says, well, why aren't you teaching these guys more than this?
Well, he forgets that he didn't have that when he got out there ten years ago, either.
He was probably more dumb than that one was.
But he forgets that, see?
And that...
They come back to us, you know, why don't you train them better, you know, teach them better.
Well, we're teaching them better every year.
It gets better every year.
It gets more complicated every year.
And it's perception they have.
It's not the fact.
Are most people in the faculty here members of the Texas TDMA?
Most, but many are not.
Are the Texans primarily?
I mean, you have vets.
veterinary medicine researchers here who do not get to reason with Texans.
Oh, yeah, we have a lot of faculty.
I mean, is there a relationship between those who are Texans who joined versus those who are not?
I don't know that there's...
I don't know.
I would guess that the out-of-staters probably relate to the TVMA better than the men's team.
Oh, do you?
I would guess that.
I don't know that's the case, but I think the reason the faculty doesn't, a number of the faculty members do not join the TVMA is that they see no direct advantage to them personally.
Yeah, you don't get professional...
We have a bunch of them around here that we call clinical associates that are here for three years and have gone somewhere else.
They're really graduate students.
And they don't see any reason for joining here, going somewhere else.
And you have to think about the TVMA mostly is composed of private clinical practitioners.
The examining board, Texas Veterinary Medical Examining Board, by law, every member has to be a private clinical practitioner.
And private clinical practitioners are working for private clinical practitioners.
You go to a TVMA meeting and you'll have very little about academia.
in that TVMA meeting.
It's the practice, the private clinical practice of veterinary medicine.
So the faculty goes and they see these things and they say, well, where do we come in?
They're not doing anything for us, you see.
Well, they are doing things for us.
They're doing things for the profession.
And they're vital to the profession, even though it's not directly maybe helping me here as a teacher in the College of Veterinary Medicine.
it's helping me because it's helping my profession.
And we have the same thing, I guess, in history.
So there gets to be a little bit of, you know.
Which raises another question.
You've mentioned over again, and I believe you implicitly, that, you know, veterinary medicine is reactive.
It reacts to what people want.
How does academia find out
I would think the TVMA, for example, would be a resource for academia, for example, to go and talk to practicing veterinarians and kind of, what's out there?
What's happening?
Where's, you know... Well, of course, technology.
We established this right here in the clinics.
That's first.
That veterinarian out there doesn't get that first.
We get it here.
And then we bring him in for a...
seminar or the continuing education program and we show him what this is and we train him right there.
Now he's probably the only practitioner out there and they come here on weekends to seminars and conferences and we're teaching people out there all the time.
So generally they perceive you as a major resource for their profession and their livelihood and everything else.
Well, it is.
That's more than a perception.
Without the College of Veterinary Medicine here, they'd have to be going to Oklahoma State or somewhere else to get the same thing.
Well, that's a good thing we can develop in terms of the relationship.
Dr.
Bright, I don't want to burn you out today.
I'm enjoying it.
I am, too.
But I guess maybe we'll come back to you time and time.
But I wonder, would you comment on this again in very broad terms, perhaps, on some people or outstanding accomplishments, outstanding individuals, major problems.
Don't elaborate, but sort of point things out to us that you think we should be aware of, possibly, that you feel that we might otherwise overlook.
And I don't know what kind of question that is either.
Well, I don't either.
Well, let me give you a for instance.
One of the things I'm wondering about is horse racing and how that's going to impact veterinarians ethically and practitioner sense and every other way.
That's obviously a current kind of thing.
Oh yeah, I understand.
As a for instance, I mean, there's dozens of others.
Well, I think the, uh, we already hear our students talk about equine practice more than we did.
They picked that up, you know, that horses, races, takes in some, uh, horses are going to need some care.
And, uh, they like horses.
Even the little girls that fell in love with a horse, you know, that's attractive.
I could be an equine practitioner.
I've dealt with horses.
I've ridden horses, you know, and trained horses and all that.
Hey, that beat is natural for me.
Yeah, they're talking about that.
And I would expect we will be putting more people out there in equine practice.
That's one simple veterinary entire.
I can't remember what it was.
I was saying that veterinary medicine in Texas really began with the,
basically equine practice, that people were more concerned about their horses than anything else in the early days.
So we might be coming back to that.
Horses are different.
Don't forget mules.
The mules, yeah.
They were very important.
Well, that's true.
You know, we used to be called horse doctors.
Yeah, that's right.
H-O-S-S, horse doctors.
Horse doctors, yeah.
Mr. Ben Green's book is that horse doctors.
What about some either interesting, unusual, or exciting people in the business, or in the profession here at the college?
Things that are going on that you think are most fascinating.
To think.
Any time.
Or that have occurred.
Like, where you saw that, you know,
the history of academic veterinary medicine in Texas has been until more recent years, I would say the last 20 years, has been that we
We trained, trained, not educated, trained private clinical practitioners, large animal practitioners, and we had a national reputation for doing that.
Well, that's what people were calling for, and that's what we did.
Well, that's changed, and we've changed.
We've had to change.
And that's not what we're looking for today.
And the people who are really in the College of Veterinary Medicine making an impact on veterinary medicine, other than turning out veterinarians, is the researchers.
And we're getting better at it, day by day.
And we're doing some things that, you know,
On the cutting edge of technology, we're getting in deep into the molecular level of things, the genetic engineering side of it.
There's a great opportunity that we can come up with some of the congenital abnormalities
and change that by a genetic engine.
And that's the way out there, you know.
And we're in it today.
We've got some good people in it.
Now, does the practice of veterinary medicine do a lot with nutrition?
Well, not enough.
I can see this is another one of those gray areas.
Most of this now is really left to the
I might say that we've been a little default.
I'm trying to correct it now, but we've been a little default of not giving our graduate veterinarians enough about nutrition.
They were pretty ignorant in nutrition.
Now, you go out in farmland, I'm talking about, and you say what to feed an old cow.
If you don't know, well, you'd look pretty dumb if you're a veterinarian, you see.
And that needed to be corrected, even though it lies in the hands of a husbandry.
And that's where it should be produced, but our veterinarians need to know that also.
and not get caught short anyway, you see.
Are you getting people now moving, I guess I'm sure you are, but exotic animals, areas, zoos, etc.
Sea world.
Yeah.
We have a lot of students that want to do that.
And I know you got a lot of publicity with your, what's the sea marine animal?
guy who took care of the whales or something.
I know that caught a lot of attention, but is that part of a real developing area of veterinary medicine?
You're talking about the guy who is now at the
naval base in California.
I suppose, but he was doing all that work on those.
Yeah, on whales and stuff.
Harpuses and all that.
